If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs will no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalcarbons have an effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalcarbons are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently from all the medicines used today, and that is why they can solve the resistance problem.
In their work scientists find new, ‘better’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalcarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are united by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
