A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, which has so far been characterized by challenging positions and mutual recriminations, attracted renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations that carry most of the burden on their shoulders in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, with over 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Developed by a UN ad hoc working group, the text does not talk about how much money the rich countries would give to the poor to cope with global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of the global temperature increase that political strategies would be willing to tolerate.
This gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, High Representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's top climate officer, Yvo de Bóer, described as "the great panorama."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 between 25 and 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would reduce their emissions during the same period between 15 and 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions between 50 and 95 percent towards 2050.
The European Union also stimulated the talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.600 million annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
However, Friday was presented the same kind of artificial verbal fires that dominated the talks last week.
The United States Special Climate Envoy, Todd Stern, rejected the claims that required mandatory greenhouse gas emission reductions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if not funded by the developed world.
Manoeuvre indicated that the Obama administration is adopting a tougher line with China, with respect to what Bush administration officials did only two years ago.
The United States is not going to make an agreement without the major developing countries moving forward and taking action, Stern said, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after the Chinese Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs He Yafei, stated that the United States' highest climate negotiator lacked "common feeling," or was "very irresponsible" because he said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to cope with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, the lines of failure have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States facing their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries in the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the most courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the main powers are discussing who should cost the costs to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the large emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, supported Ulate, who also works as regional councillor on climate change in Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the major participants said that the talks would ultimately produce a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, prepared a proposal for a 24-page preliminary treaty early on the morning of Friday.
Artur Runge-Metzger, leading international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said that the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the whole political process," partly because they are now unified and require action by emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks assumed a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues must be resolved before the heads of government conclude a deal.
High-level officials, such as the Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese vice minister, descended from the planes and raced to the streets of the Bella Center, to meetings at closed doors and press conferences, in order to be able to define the claims that will be arbitrate during the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention centre, activists playing the guitar present night performances mocking the countries that they believe are being sold, and preliminary hand proposals are passed by hand rather than by mail), presents a challenge.
