The 62-year-old photographer, known for his pictures of stars of the show, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime whose sentence consists of a maximum sentence of three years of imprisonment and 375,000 euros of fine.
This means that in this case there will be a process worthy of a saga about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter dispute the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetic empire.
But Correctional Court No. 15 also ordered that 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt be subjected to a medical examination by three medical professionals.
L'Oréal's heir and main shareholder has always refused to submit to such examinations, even under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed this Friday shall submit a report by 10 March 2010 in which they must state whether Liliane Bettencourt suffered from weakness and during what periods.
I think you'll accept.
I'm going to talk to her, declared Mrs. Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman, on leaving the hearing.
For his part, Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' lawyer Olivier Metzner was pleased with the court decision.
It is an excellent news (...) The expert will show that he (Banier) manipulated this older lady, whom we must protect, said.
For two years now, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter started criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, photographer and multifaceted artist, accusing him of having taken advantage of her mother's weakness for years in order to obtain a billion euros in donations, through cheques, life insurance contracts or works of art.
For his part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied having been manipulated by the photographer, whom he considers to be a long-standing friend.
On Friday, while the court was examining the origin of the action brought by Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' allegations were, on occasion, a great family confession.
In this way, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer took into account three letters that her client sent (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary in which she said she mistrusted Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers' husband.
In the letter of 2003, Liliane Bettencourt added, as counsel: "I could explain to my daughter who wrote to Banier between one and two times a day for fifteen years.
From his wedding, I could never speak to Françoise again."
On the other hand, the National Prosecutor's Office of Nanterre once again considered that the plaintiff was not in a position to appear, especially since a guardian judge had refused, in the last few days, to give rise to his request to open a judicial custody procedure for his mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to appear before justice, is not under custody and has no guardian.
No other person may appear in place," said the representative of the Public Prosecutor's Office, Marie-Christine Daubigney.
Finally, the court decided that the judgment on the admissibility of Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers would be handed down.
Management Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with regard to their employees recalls the position of companies with regard to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees joining the "values" determined from above as before that it was intended to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquest of the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the preference factors of the customers is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end up in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially of R & D and, even more, of business intelligence.
In fact, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a prospective vision"; employees need a commitment that is entirely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting the employees in the centre of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion surveys have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion surveys, such as Orange's questionnaire among its employees, encourage management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many times, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Last, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the major engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanically.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the ancient conductist theory that the U.S. "no-sciences" recently re-activated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the executives' engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanical management position, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilisation factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the good functioning of modern companies involves adopting a finalist view of human behavior.
It consists of integrating in all business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motif Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a default dosage that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and re-use the management of human resources "in place".
In this way, they create a favourable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
