The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa found the same look as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal of two meters long and 1.50 meters tall that ran over the two strong hind legs, had a broad head with sharp teeth and curves, short arms with hoz-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa foundae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of Texas University in Austin and colleagues in the Science magazine on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards early evolution of dinosaurs, comments Nesbitt.
It shows us much about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in Ghost Ranch in northern Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found in one day a dozen dinosaur bones, this is something unprecedented for Triasic sediments, reports Randall Irmis member of the Utah Natural History Museum team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were brought together in total.
A finding confirms the theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt is an exceptional finding: "Triasic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other experts in dinosaurs do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs appeared for the first time about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
The experts thus discuss, for example, when the sauries were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous teropods among those found in Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velocipator and also birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivoros (sauriums with bird pelvis), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus belong.
According to Nesbitt's analysis and his colleagues, Tawa foundae is a primitive teropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, comments Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa, researchers found signs of airbags, such as those that also own the descendants of the teropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, bird breathing is more efficient than mammals.
In the case of Tawa also found the bones of the spine were evidently filled with air in part.
Tawa is the teropod with the oldest and most primitive airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migratory waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers suggest that the sauris appeared there for the first time.
Therefore, the three genealogical lines separated at first and spread from South America through all corners of the earth, which by that time still formed a unique earth mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa found the remains of two other not very closely related teropods.
The three cannot descend from a single parenter, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three migratory waves have been given to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, who belongs to a group of brothers from dinosaurs, lived in the present-day Poland, comments the paleontologist of Bonn Martin Sander.
Your opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many fossils of dinosaurs continue to be preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs evolved from a relatively rare sideline from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in Triasic dinosaurs still shared their vital space with many other reptiles, for example, the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosauri and many other sauris.
Towards the end of the Triasic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the limit of the Triasic towards the Jurassic.
Successive Stories Were Not Eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It may have given a massive extinction to which dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the competitors in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact brakes the rise of a group of species, which had already evolved in the Triasic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
